1. EXPLORATORY DATA ANALYSIS¶

Now we will use a dataset with more information of the cases of Covid and the evolution in the hospitals. You can find the updated dataset: https://analisi.transparenciacatalunya.cat/Salut/Dades-di-ries-de-COVID-19-per-comarca/c7sd-zy9j

In this new dataset we have:

  • Number of daily PCRs.
  • Positive tests by a PCR.
  • Daily deaths.
  • Daily ICU entries.
  • Daily general entries in hospitals.

In [17]:
#plot a column of the dataframe with a date interval
def scatter_plot_days(variable,data,inter):
    dates = pd.to_datetime(data['DATA'])
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 5))
    ax.grid()
    ax.scatter(dates,data[variable],c='grey')
    ax.set(xlabel='Data',ylabel=variable,title=variable)
    date_form = dt.DateFormatter("%d-%m")
    ax.xaxis.set_major_formatter(date_form)
    ax.xaxis.set_major_locator(dt.DayLocator(interval = inter))
    plt.show()

With the derived variable we will train a liner regression to predict when the deaths and the positivity rate will become 0. For this, we will use the cases after the peak.

2.1 Building a linear model¶

In [29]:
def linear_regression_cov(data, var,days_forward,intervalplot):
    # # let's train our model only with data after the peak
    peak = data[var].idxmax()
    X_train = [[i] for i in range(peak,len(data[var])-1)] #days after the peak 
    y = data[var].tolist()[1:]
    y_train = y[peak:]

    model = linear_model.LinearRegression()
    # Train the model using the training sets
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    print ("Linear Regression Model Score: " + str(model.score(X_train, y_train)))
    y_pred = model.predict(X_train)
    error = max_error(y_train, y_pred)
    X_test = [[i] for i in range(peak,peak+days_forward)]
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

    #boundaries with the error
    y_pred_max = []
    y_pred_min = []
    for i in range(0, len(y_pred)):
        y_pred_max.append(y_pred[i] + error)
        y_pred_min.append(y_pred[i] - error)

    #data info to plot 
    d =str(data[data[var].idxmax() == data.index].DATA.values[0])
    date_zero = datetime.datetime.strptime(d[:10],'%Y-%m-%d')
    date_prev = []
    x_ticks = []
    step = 5
    data_curr = date_zero
    x_current = peak
    n = int(days_forward / step)
    for i in range(0, n + intervalplot):
        date_prev.append(str(data_curr.day) + "/" + str(data_curr.month))
        x_ticks.append(x_current)
        data_curr = data_curr + timedelta(days=step)
        x_current = x_current + step
    
    plt.grid()
    plt.scatter(X_train, y_train,c = 'lightblue',label = "Derived Variable")
    # plot linear regression prediction
    plt.plot(X_test, y_pred, color='blue', linewidth=2, label = 'Predicted')
    # plot maximum error
    plt.plot(X_test, y_pred_max, color='gray', linewidth=1, linestyle='dashed')
    #plot minimum error
    plt.plot(X_test, y_pred_min, color='gray', linewidth=1, linestyle='dashed')
    
    plt.xlabel('Days')
    plt.xlim(peak, peak + days_forward)
    plt.xticks(x_ticks, date_prev)
    
    plt.ylabel(var)
    plt.yscale("log")
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

We build X_test with the number of days forward we want our model to predict (remember that the once the number of cases peaked in March, until end of May the curve of cases did not decrease, so at least two months!).

3. SIR MODEL¶

The SIR model describes the evolution of an epidemic labeling the population into three groups:

  • Susceptible: Population that can get infected.
  • Infectious: Population infected at a time t.
  • Recovered: Population that has recovered and has a supposed immunity (we will suppose that for Covid there is a 3 months immunity, even though this is not proven).

The flow of the epidemic is understood as follows:

3.1 Differential equations for SIR model¶

We define the SIR differential equations as follows:

In [36]:
def SIR(x, t, beta, gamma):
    s, i, r = x
    dsdt = -beta * s * i
    didt = beta * s * i - gamma * i
    drdt =  gamma * i
    return [dsdt, didt, drdt]

3.2 Estimating parameters¶

The main parameters of the SIR model are the basic reproduction number R0, the rate of recovery and the transmission rate . With this we can model the evolution t days forward.

  • R0: basic reproduction number, rate of infection. Measures the amount of people an infected individual can infect. To have the pandemic under control it should be < 1.

  • : rate of recovery of infections. The inverse of the time it takes for an individual to overcome the infection. For the covid-19 we suppose 6-7 days.

  • : transmission rate. Computed by the product of the rate of infection and the rate of recovery measures the new infections.

As for the active cases, we will sum the cases in the last 7 days and when the data was last updated, the R0 was 0.98 and in a positive trend. We will make some tests to see what can happen with different values of R0.

In [37]:
infected = data[data.DATA >= str(date(2020,11,29))] #last 7 days 
healed = data[data.DATA < str(date(2020,11,28))]
healed=  healed[healed.DATA >= str(date(2020,9,28))] #we suppose that there is a 3 month immunity

##computing the number of infected
activeCases = infected.CASOS_CONFIRMAT.sum()
cases = healed.CASOS_CONFIRMAT.sum()

population = 7.566*10**6 #set population
In [38]:
def setSIRparameters(R0,infective_days,days_forward):
        
    # initial S,I,R
    i_initial = activeCases / population #initial infected
    r_initial = cases / population#0  #people who has already been infected (recovered)
    s_initial = 1 - i_initial - r_initial
    
    #set parameters
    gamma = 1/infective_days #rate of recovery 
    beta = R0*gamma #transmission rate
    
    #set time parameters
    t = np.linspace(0, days_forward, 2000)
    
    return beta, gamma, i_initial,r_initial,s_initial,t

3.3 Plotting the results for different values of R0.¶

We define two functions to plot the output of the SIR model.

In [39]:
#plots the susceptible, the infected and the recovered for a time t
def plotSIR(t,sirmodel):    
    S, I, R = sirmodel.T

    fig = plt.figure(facecolor='w')

    ax = fig.add_subplot(111, axisbelow=True)

    ax.plot(t, S, 'b', alpha=0.5, lw=2, label='Susceptible')
    ax.plot(t, I ,'r', alpha=0.5, lw=2, label='Infected')
    ax.plot(t, R, 'g', alpha=0.5, lw=2, label='Recovered')
    
    ax.set_xlabel('Time in days')
    ax.set_ylabel('Population in percentage')
    legend = ax.legend()

    plt.title("SIR Model")
    plt.show()
In [40]:
#plots the infected
def plotInfected(i):
    fig = plt.figure(facecolor='w')

    ax = fig.add_subplot(111, axisbelow=True)

    ax.plot(t, i ,'r', alpha=0.5, lw=2, label='Infected')
    
    ax.set_xlabel('Time in days')
    ax.set_ylabel('Population in percentage')
    legend = ax.legend()

    plt.title("Infected population")
    plt.show()

3.3.1 R0 maintains a value < 1, R0=0.98¶

In this scenario, we are decreasing the positive cases and "controlling the epidemic. It is a danger zone because it is too close to 1 and the trend can easily change.

In [41]:
b, g,i_0,r_0,s_0,t = setSIRparameters(R0 = 0.98,infective_days= 7,days_forward = 60)
#initial conditions
x_initial =  s_0,i_0,r_0
sirmodel = odeint(SIR, x_initial, t, args=(b, g))
#plot s,i,r
plotSIR(t,sirmodel) 
#plot infected
s, i, r = sirmodel.T
plotInfected(i)

3.3.2 R0 increases to 1.1¶

Just increasing a bit R0 we see a much more different scenario: positive cases start to rise and it would take almost a year to stabilize the situation.

In [42]:

3.3.3 R0 increases to 2¶

Critic scenario: each person infects 2 more persons. If for 2 months straight the R0 does not decrease we would be in a critic situation. After 50 days, 40% of the population would be infected and by the end of the 3 months only a 20% of the population would be susceptible of catching the virus (that is, not infected). This situation would bring ICU saturations and an increase in the deaths numbers.

In [43]:
b, g,i_0,r_0,s_0,t = setSIRparameters(R0 = 2,infective_days= 7,days_forward = 120)
x_initial =  s_0,i_0,r_0

#plot s,i,r
plotSIR(t,sirmodel) 

#plot infected

4. CONCLUSIONS¶

  1. About the data:
    • Increasing the testing helps in the contention of the pandemic, positivity helps predicting the number of cases.
    • It would be useful to have the data of hospitals admissions during the first wave, since it is a relevant information for the second wave.
    • Measures such as social distancing and closing restauration does have an effect in the pandemic evolution.
  1. About the Linear model:
    • It predicts well the end of the first wave and it is useful to predict the behaviour of the evolution of the pandemic.
    • Probably, if all measures had remained intact in December, the number of cases would have decreased by 15th December.
  1. About the SIR model:
    • Social distancing is probably the most efficient measure to contain the pandemic: when the R0 decreases fast so does the number of new positives.
    • It is dangerous to have the R0 over 1.
